<p>YEM 6/2011 
<b>Yemen 
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p><b>Summary 
</b></p>
<p><b>executions;  
</b></p>
<p><b>Terrorism;   
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>Alleged targeted killing through a United States drone attack. According to the information 
received, on 30 September 2011, Mr. Anwar al-Awlaki, Mr. Samir Khan and several others were 
killed by a drone strike in Khasef, Jawf province, Yemen. Unconfirmed reports indicate that they 
were hit by a United States drone. It was alleged that Mr. Al-Awlaki, his son Abdulrahman, 
believed to have been 16 years of age, and Mr. Khan became the second, third and fourth United 
States citizens subjected to a targeted killing through a United States drone attack in Yemen 
following the killing of Mr. Kamal Derwish in 2002. It is further alleged that, unlike in other 
countries, where the United States Central Intelligence Agency reportedly enjoys a blanket 
authorization by President Obama to carry out drone strikes at will, each attack in Yemen 
requires individual approval by the President. Such an authorization was reportedly based on an 
interdepartmental legal memorandum of June 2010 prepared under the lead of the U.S. Justice 
Department&#8223;s Office of Legal Counsel. See as well case no. USA 20/2011 above sent on 2 
November 2011. 
</p>
<p> 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
</p>
